There is one more detail I am curious about: the OpenAI integration was pre=
sented as being a part of Apple Intelligence, which is only available on th=
e latest devices; the cut-off for Apple Intelligence, in my estimation, is =
having a minimum of 8GB of RAM (and of course Apple Silicon). However, Open=
AI operates entirely in the cloud; it follows, then, that Apple could bring=
 the OpenAI integration to all of its devices; however, it does not appear =
that it will do so.

The most obvious explanation is that Apple doesn=E2=80=99t want to muddy th=
e waters in terms of what Apple Intelligence is and isn=E2=80=99t; it is al=
so possible that Apple needs Apple Intelligence to know what requests to ro=
ute to OpenAI. Both reasons make sense, but if this does become a major mon=
ey-maker for Apple it is worth noting that this is a lever they could poten=
tially pull in the future.

As for OpenAI, this does seem like a pretty crazy bet. On one hand, yes, th=
ey are getting =E2=80=9CChatGPT=E2=80=9D put in front of hundreds of millio=
ns of users, at least over time as devices that support Apple Intelligence =
are being sold, and sure, there might be money to be made there; I=E2=80=99=
m going to assume that the 10 messages in 24 hour limit that currently appl=
ies to chatgpt.com will apply to this integration, which has the potential =
to be a big upsell. Still, that is a lot of inference costs that OpenAI is =
signing up for! It might, though, be crazy like a fox:

* Microsoft, who is ultimately on the hook for the compute necessary to pow=
er this integration, has a deep dependency on OpenAI for not just Azure and=
 its own products but, in many respects, its entire valuation.
* Apple may be seeking to Aggregate AI providers, but for now the only one =
that is signed up is OpenAI; until it has alternatives in place it is commi=
tted to making sure this integration delivers.

In other words, you can, if you squint, see a bit of moral hazard in this b=
et: there are upsides for OpenAI in terms of securing their position as the=
 dominant consumer chatbot company, and you could see how CEO Sam Altman mi=
ght believe that the company has the leverage to go for that upside even if=
 there is the potential that usage costs end up swamping the service.

Japan and the App Store
-----------------------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2024/6/13/24177599/apple-google-j=
apan-law-third-party-app-stores-competition ) :

Following in the footsteps of the European Union, Japan has now passed a la=
w that will restrict Apple and Google from blocking third-party app stores =
for Japanese users on their platforms. The legislation is expected to come =
into force by the end of 2025 and aims to reduce app prices and create a mo=
re equitable market by forcing the tech giants to compete with smaller chal=
lengers.

Dubbed the Act on Promotion of Competition for Specified Smartphone Softwar=
e, Japan=E2=80=99s law shares some similarities with the EU=E2=80=99s Digit=
al Markets Act (DMA), enforcing strict rules against =E2=80=9Cdesignated pr=
oviders.=E2=80=9D That includes requiring their platforms to allow third-pa=
rty app stores, allowing app developers to offer third-party billing servic=
es, and making it easier for users to change their default settings and web=
 browsers. The law also prevents tech giants from prioritizing their own se=
rvices in search results, something Google was targeted for under its own D=
MA enforcements.

Apple and Google have already been named designated providers, and any furt=
her additions will be selected by Japan=E2=80=99s Fair Trade Commission (FT=
C). Providers that violate the rules face being fined up to 20 percent of t=
he domestic revenue specific to the infringing service, which increases to =
30 percent for repeat offenses.

John Gruber has an interesting take at Daring Fireball ( https://daringfire=
ball.net/linked/2024/06/15/japan-app-stores ) , noting that Japan isn=E2=80=
=99t naming Nintendo or Sony designated providers, even though they have ev=
en more stringent app stores for their consoles (Gruber also notes that Jap=
an, reasonably, is basing fines on Japan-derived revenue, as opposed to the=
 EU=E2=80=99s overreach of basing fines on worldwide revenue). It=E2=80=99s=
 a good take that harkens back to one of our long-running debates on Dither=
ing ( https://dithering.fm/ ) : is it reasonable to analogize iPhone and An=
droid to gaming consoles? It does make sense in terms of games specifically=
, which drive the vast majority of App Store revenues; indeed, my objection=
 to the App Store has always been about non-game applications, which is why=
