Apple=E2=80=99s AI Developer Risk
-------------------------

In last week=E2=80=99s second post-WWDC update ( https://stratechery.com/20=
24/wwdc-apple-intelligence-apple-aggregates-ai/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJS=
UzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.ey=
JhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyW=
URLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L3d3=
ZGMtYXBwbGUtaW50ZWxsaWdlbmNlLWFwcGxlLWFnZ3JlZ2F0ZXMtYWkvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MjE=
yMTA4NzQsImlhdCI6MTcxODYxODg3NCwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW=
5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0Z=
Wdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwi=
dXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.DU2E8g-Qma0Nn3xcHCTDplItxpbPNWRw_2KxRV1126lCf2TE5Y5auN2=
Yh0Vx8xs8EGzZCScRLXs5M21vGnYenv9MQD6U6j1kT0sOxvTcrMt_0cMWZcH8EU4vnJdZWRtMV3=
oKX8KFlXowg5zRyz3tkQCvD_gP4508NaGNJWkFdtkshZiJ32-MJNPJemZkfM93Tmeyl4QwvJ1Gr=
ixiWGbEgSa-mH4lRlGvrqr7OzViZqUjpt2qxF-aJ5nJpvCMrgpvw1LUSUucDL4w1IYdPfKcanWN=
fAeVoBYbE3GGcHLDDGubD5WanDNGvtMYy4nchFCuwmmc6EAVI9dg5qSaTXKcHA ) I wrote:

The other piece of this illustration to call out is the =E2=80=9CApp Intent=
s Toolbox=E2=80=9D; this is the list of developer-defined actions exposed b=
y apps to the operating system. To date app intents have been utilized for =
Siri, Shortcuts, and Spotlight; going forward app intents will be leveraged=
 by Apple Intelligence to accomplish tasks across apps, again via RAG.

What is fascinating to consider is the extent to which these intents might =
be a Faustian bargain for developers: the implication of exposing functiona=
lity to Apple Intelligence is that the user interface of an app is diminish=
ed in importance; this is fine for apps that have differentiated resources =
that are not dependent on owning the user interface, but it does provide a =
long-run existential risk to apps that rely on user attention (in the most =
obvious use case, to show ads). The power of an Aggregator, though, is to c=
ompel suppliers like app developers to deliver functionality on their terms=
, so to the extent that Apple Intelligence becomes a meaningful interface f=
or accomplishing things on your phone, is the extent to which developers wi=
ll have to run the risk of losing user attention even as they deliver user =
benefits.

Apple=E2=80=99s problems with regulators is one thing; any sort of diminish=
ment in its power over developers is being revealed as something much more =
serious. Consider the Vision Pro; shortly before the device launched I wrot=
e about The Apple Vision Pro=E2=80=99s Missing Apps ( https://stratechery.c=
om/2024/the-apple-vision-pros-missing-apps/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1=
NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdW=
QiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLY=
mZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L3RoZS1h=
cHBsZS12aXNpb24tcHJvcy1taXNzaW5nLWFwcHMvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MjEyMTA4NzQsImlhdCI=
6MTcxODYxODg3NCwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2=
NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlb=
nRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNz=
In0.gqe2BmyfDFwvq4lSZB9eSTeVJtr7Go5hmGVUUrdZDnK3mH4-kqPwPq8FcwP_J1lIaERRMCI=
jAQ8znyqaGVqlnQEjvyrSAFGbwLMIRso7CW-XjBaMB-7tx8qxDF287OMsmxs3GUR4XDGyZ1B4rU=
cBEsoZTdQZ2FmkkEZyccPdNiZaamCuFDVO85ZzXps3P6EaM2p2s8YEQW46QdhdLeBfzbFhaQWQ0=
hgQ0Uz-tOY72tNNdb3ykxzgk1JkhBE992hx7HX-m3Hji4wgFv8MIRm5c6U2Dib7ngvitugj-Q-R=
3i3Z2vYDMJ57yN2vn80Gg5_5OY8LtPzGGgNqpibA_AfNVw ) :

It=E2=80=99s certainly possible that I=E2=80=99m reading too much into thes=
e absences: maybe these three companies simply didn=E2=80=99t get enough Vi=
sions Pro to build a native app, and felt uncomfortable releasing their iPa=
d versions without knowing how useful they would be. YouTube in particular,=
 given that much of its usage is free, likely has less of a beef with Apple=
 than Netflix or Spotify do, and it=E2=80=99s easy enough to believe that G=
oogle just isn=E2=80=99t a company that moves that fast these days.

Still, there=E2=80=99s no question that the biggest beneficiary of these co=
mpanies being on the Vision Pro =E2=80=94 and, correspondingly, the biggest=
 loser from their absence =E2=80=94 is Apple. The company is launching an a=
udacious and ambitious new product, and there are major partners in its eco=
system that aren=E2=80=99t interested in helping.

This is the consequence of fashioning App Store policies as a stick: until =
there is a carrot of a massive user base, it=E2=80=99s hard to see why deve=
lopers of any size would be particularly motivated to build experiences for=
 the Vision Pro, which will make it that much more difficult to attract sai=
d massive user base. Apple was happy to remind users that, when it came to =
the iPhone, there=E2=80=99s an app for that ( https://www.youtube.com/watch=
?v=3DszrsfeyLzyg ) ; in the case of the Vision Pro, there may not be: this =
is the one and only chance for developers to go on strike without suffering=
 an Epic-like fate, and some of them are taking it.

Apple=E2=80=99s best chance of getting developers on board the Vision Pro w=
as before the device shipped: that is the time when the company could sell =
potential; now the company has to deal with numbers, and given the fact tha=
t WWDC didn=E2=80=99t include any of them, it=E2=80=99s probably safe to as=
sume they aren=E2=80=99t great. What is notable, though, is that Apple had =
the need to sell at all: perhaps I=E2=80=99m looking at the past with rose-=
colored glasses, but it seems to me that the company used to have developer=
s eager to support its latest initiatives no-questions-asked just because d=
evelopers loved Apple; now, they don=E2=80=99t so much, and the App Store =
=E2=80=94 and in particular, Apple=E2=80=99s rhetoric about the App Store =
=E2=80=94 is largely to blame.

Fast forward to AI, and the best case for Apple is that developers eagerly =
embrace App Intents such that Apple Intelligence can smartly leverage a hug=
e number of 3rd-party apps on day one. It seems to me that, had Apple pushe=
d App Intents with the promise of integrating with a super-advanced Siri a =
decade ago, most developers would have jumped in immediately without seriou=
s consideration to the long-term risks to their business I noted above; tod=
ay, though, developers are much more likely to take a step back and critica=
lly consider their position relative to the iPhone maker.

In other words, I think you can make the case that Apple=E2=80=99s intransi=
gent approach to the App Store is actually one of the biggest risk factors =
for Apple Intelligence: the effectiveness of Apple Intelligence will in man=
y respects rest on the willingness of app developers to plug into Apple=E2=
=80=99s overall system; doing so, though, may not be optimal for many apps.=
 Apple=E2=80=99s problem is that they have inspired developers to look at t=
heir interactions with the company with a far more cynical and self-interes=
ted eye than they did previously; giving in just a little bit with the App =
Store might have made this into a different story, allowing Apple to retain=
 the developer eagerness of old.

It=E2=80=99s possible, of course, that I am overstating my case and overly-=
romanticizing the previous relationship between Apple and developers. Maybe=
 both sides were always coldly rational, and will be going forward: it=E2=
=80=99s possible that the iPhone is such an important platform that develop=
ers will get in line, much as OpenAI did in terms of their partnership with=
 Apple. I suspect, though, that Apple=E2=80=99s AI dreams would be in a bet=
ter place had the company given just a sliver of ground with the App Store.

